			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">strange that a melee can swap in a weapon with a higher dmg component and hit for, yeah more dmg, yet we give that to our pet, and he still hits for 85.. riiiiight, makes a whole lot of sense.. 
<br />

<br />
my level 55 sk hits for 280's right now. ghetto thanks..</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Your SK is most likely using a high damage 2hs like a Windblade right?  If you understand melee game mechanics and how damage bonuses for high delay weapons adjusts the total max hit, you wouldn't use this as a reference.  The pet is a warrior (for all intensive purposes).  He duel wields and quads.  Compare your 85 hitting pet to the average 65 warrior using such weapons like a BoC and Split Blade of Destruction (decent combo for a non raid-guild warrior) and you will find his average hit is most likely lower than 85.  Can he hit for more than 85? Slightly yes, consistantly? No, talk to the RNG on this one, lol.  You also have to take into account he has a damage bonus applied to his mainhand weapon but not offhand, so even wielding 2 exact damage weapons he cannot hit for the same amount with both hands, like a pet does.
<br />

<br />
Compare your SK hitting for 280 with his 2hs with a 44 delay weapon before haste(still assuming WB here as it is a popular twink 2hs) and I am sure factoring in the delay of your pet w/muzzle and BO5 to your SK with CoM + VoQ,  I am pretty certain the pet will still put out greater DPS than the SK at 55.  Max hit means nothing compared to overall DPS.
<br />

<br />
Elder Longfanz Beaztmaster Feral Lord</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
